feedback: I looked at how many features each family generally had, not based on which features.
I tried to find a pattern, but was unsuccessful.
i remembered a couple easy to remember things and guessed the rest
I tried to remember which of the 3 features appeared in each figure for each group the most and also which configurations of features were showing the most in each group
If a pattern could occur in either family I chose the higher prevalence family otherwise I'd be randomly guessing. I memorizes hat pattern belonged most with a family.
it seemed to me that family a tended toward having feature 1 and 2, while family b tended toward feature 2 and 3

I tried to look for patterns of numbers of features. So if one item had only one feature, it might belong to one family. But if it had 2 or 3, it might belong to the other. That was the easiest way I could keep track, but it is far from perfect.

The first set was fairly clear. If it had one feature it was a 1, more than 1 feature was a 2. The second set was more unclear. If it had one feature it was normally a 2 and if it had 3 features it was normally a 1, but 2 features was split fairly evenly, so those were a little more difficult.

I could not easily find much of a common feature for either family. Trying to keep in mind the features of 100 images and comparing the amount of them is clearly too difficult of a task, so I chose by thinking of the features that I felt appeared a little often in one family. Since the instructions also said that there would be about half from one family and half from the other, I tried to divide the features up in a like a percentage. For example, I thought Feature 3 appeared about 80% of the time in Family 1, so I tried to divide it up to mostly Family 1 but chose some for Family 2.

I tried memorizing what families each figure belonged to. What I noticed was that all the figures presented belonged to both families (so 50/50 split). It took me a while to realize it, but any choice presented when choosing which family the figure belonged to would be correct.
TRIED TO FIGURE OUT A PATTERN WAS IT ODD EVEN THEN MEMORIZE PIECES

In the first round, with the bodies, it seemed like Family 1 preferred legs and arms, while the second family preferred either a whole body or the arms. I'm not sure if that's right or now.
 
The second round seemed like Family 1 preferred whole faces, the eyes and nose together or the mouth and nose together. Family 2 seemed to like the nose and mouth a lot.
I noticed that one family had most of the "all three feature" ones. Other than that I tried to memorize which things I saw mostly in 1.

In the first one, I thought the first group usually had fewer parts than the second, and was more likely to have a head. In the second categorization task, I wasn't really sure, except that I thought the whole face was usually in the first group
I mostly relied on which family had the most complete set of features, that was the most helpful in narrowing down who belonged to which family.
I just tried to identify what I thought were more likely traits in each family and made my best guesses.

On the first take the combinations were almost always family 2 while the single parts were almost always family 1. On the second taks it was mostly the same combo were family 1 and singles were family 2. There were some that seemed to be 50/50 so I just changed those occasionally.

I tried to remember what was missing from the parts in each family and what was included.  I tried to see what was common to each one and the decided to only look for the most common trait in each family and make a decision on that.
I tried to narrow it down to obvious things like the 2 family had all three attributes in the first one or the 2 family tended to only have one attribute in the 2nd trial
I just tried to figure out what features each had and looked for patterns then  decided which ones i thought went most with each family.
